                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18300916-136-victim1199 t18300916-136-viclabel714"></join>. I pulled off my jacket, at nine o'clock at night on the 6th of July, and laid it down, under the care of another <rs id="t18300916-136-deflabel715" type="occupation">boy</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18300916-136-defend1197 t18300916-136-deflabel715"></join>, on the bank of the Serpentine river: when I came out it was gone - I had seen two boys near my clothes, but I did not see the prisoner; this is the jacket - it is my master's.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18300916-136-person1202">
                  WILLIAM 
                  STEVENS
               <interp inst="t18300916-136-person1202" type="surname" value="STEVENS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300916-136-person1202" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300916-136-person1202" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am an officer. I got this jacket from the prisoner, on a coal-wharf, on the 7th of July; I had been to his lodging, but he was not there - I then went to his master, and he came in while I was there; he at first denied it, but then said he would take me to where it was- he said he took it through distress.</p>
               <p>The prisoner put in a written Defence, pleading poverty, stating himself to be an orphan, and desiring to be sent to the Refuge for the Destitute.</p>
